NL_2p1 overview

PMT detection system

The photomultiplier (PMT) detection system features 4 PMT channels, nPoint nPFocus400 piezo stage, Olympus XLUMPLFLN20XW objective, and the tissue camera. The whole system is mounted on the stepper motor Z-stage for precise and large range vertical positioning.

The photomultipliers allow highly sensitive detection of light, converting impinging photons into a small electrical current. Depending on the detection setup, it's possible to either count photons hitting the PMT sensitive area, or to measure the flux of arriving photons. The detected signal has to be then amplified and registered on a DAQ card. See Photomultiplier channels for details.

The PMT devices by themselves have little color selectivity. The spectrum of the photons which reach the PMTs is determined by the optical elements, especially filters and dichroic mirrors, which the photons encounter on their way. Below, is the information on the spectra of the filtering optical elements comprising the setup, as well as the snapshot of the 3D model of the detection setup with labeled optical elements.

The tissue camera located at the end of the red channels detection module provides a close up look at the sample through the objective, at the same depth (or close to, depending on the alignment), as where the two-photon excitation is occurring. It helps with the selection of the desired depth of the 2p recording, and allows to determine pulse from the observable blood circulation.

  • 3D model: https://a360.co/3E41DtG
  • For spectra of the optical components see PMT detection system spectra
  • For maintenance alignment see PMT detection system maintenance alignment
  • Software
    • The MC module for acquisition of PMT data is AI scanner . While this module can be used independently, it's a part of the point-scanner package and in the context of NL-2p1 microscope should be considered as such.
    • The MC module for acquisition is video-grabber .
    • The MC module for the piezo stage is nPoint nPFocus400 piezo stage
    • See Software assemblies and usage for details.
